# React Components

## One Component Per File

Each `.tsx` file must contain exactly one React component. Helpers, constants, and types used only by that component may live in the same file, but a second exported component must go in its own file.

## Named Exports Only

Always use named arrow function exports:

```tsx
export const InstructorCard = ({ name }: Props) => {
  return <div>{name}</div>;
};
```

Never use `export default` except in Next.js reserved files (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `template.tsx`, `default.tsx`). In those files, define a named export first, then re-export:

```tsx
export const HomePage = () => {
  return <div>Home</div>;
};

export default HomePage;
```

## Functional Components Only

Do not use class components. All components must be functional.

## Props

Define a `Props` type above the component. Use it directly in the function signature:

```tsx
type Props = {
  name: string;
  isActive: boolean;
};

export const InstructorCard = ({ name, isActive }: Props) => {
  return <div>{name}</div>;
};
```

If the component accepts `children`, include it explicitly in the Props type.

## Component Size

Keep components small and single-purpose. When a component exceeds ~150 lines, extract sub-components into separate files in the same `_components/` folder.

## Composition Over Prop Drilling

Prefer passing components as children or render props over passing data through many layers of props. Use React context sparingly and only for truly global state (theme, auth, locale).

## File Structure Within a Component File

Order content as:
1. Imports
2. Types
3. Constants
4. The exported component
5. Helper functions (if small and only used by this component)
